text: It’s been more than a month since protests began in Louisville following the killings of George Floyd and Breonna Taylor. Demonstrations are still going on every day — and protesters say they’ll continue until there is "justice for Breonna Taylor." https://t.co/1J63QOhdGk

name: nytimes
text:
Since May 28, the protests demanding action against the police officers involved in Breonna Taylor's killing have become a sustained movement.

Here's a look at 45 days of marches in Louisville. https://t.co/KHu48RF4fj https://t.co/WFsBrb9Rnv

name: nytimes
text: The protests were intense at first. Police officers in riot gear deployed tear gas to disperse crowds. Local officials declared a curfew. A Kentucky National Guard member shot and killed David McAtee, a local barbecue shop owner. https://t.co/KHu48RF4fj https://t.co/5fm4zvGlwx

name: nytimes
text: But after the first week, the curfew was lifted and the protests took on a new rhythm. People gathered daily at Jefferson Square Park, a downtown square turned protest rally point. On the day of Breonna Taylor’s birthday, hundreds gathered with balloons. https://t.co/KHu48RF4fj https://t.co/zt0XbeSuzY

name: nytimes
text: Tents popped up as a downtown square turned into a more permanent spot to gather. But in late June, after a protester was shot and killed there, the Louisville Metro Police Department dismantled the camps and said that the park was to be closed nightly. https://t.co/KHu48RF4fj https://t.co/keLw9Ekqyw

name: nytimes
text:
Despite the police order, people reconvened at the square the next day — and have returned every day since. 

This was the scene this past Saturday, marking 45 days since the protests began. https://t.co/KHu48RF4fj https://t.co/2eEaVqY8nJ
